etymologies: early 19th century (in an earlier sense). From French accoucher to take to one's bed for the delivery of a child, (reflexive) to give birth, to assist (a woman) in giving birth, to produce (an artistic or literary work) from a- + coucher

definitions: To deliver or unburden (of something), in the manner of a midwife; (also) to bring to general notice, as if by the action of a midwife or accoucher.

notes.text: In early use often with reference to the proverbial phrase the mountain has laboured and brought forth a mouse.
